  <h1>Common Class Action Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll get a big payout.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Headline settlement numbers are gross figures. After attorney fees (25&ndash;33%), administration costs, and division among thousands of claimants, individual shares are often $5&ndash;$50 in consumer cases. Securities and wage cases tend to pay more because individual losses are larger.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need to do anything to get paid.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>In most settlements, you must submit a valid claim form by the deadline. If you do nothing, you typically receive nothing but also release your claims against the defendant. Automatic payment (without filing) is rare and occurs only in very small settlements.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Attorneys are getting rich while I get nothing.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Fee awards are high in dollar terms because settlements are large, but courts review them for reasonableness. In cases with small per-claimant damages, the class benefit may come primarily from injunctive relief (changed business practices) rather than cash &mdash; which isn&rsquo;t reflected in individual check amounts.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t opt out.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>You can always opt out of a Rule 23(b)(3) damages class action during the exclusion period. Opting out preserves your right to sue individually. You cannot opt out of a Rule 23(b)(1) or (b)(2) class (mandatory classes for injunctive relief).</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;The settlement means the company admitted wrongdoing.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Almost never. Settlement agreements invariably include a no-admission clause. The defendant pays to resolve the litigation without conceding liability.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-class-action-settlements-work">how settlements work</a> and <a href="/guides/filing-a-class-action-claim">filing a claim</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
